<paragraph blockId="62.[151,1437,151,1293]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Benes" authorityYear="1972" box="[151,286,151,177]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,286,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Onycholyda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a compact genus, well defined by the characters given in the key (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Shinohara, A." box="[1135,1327,151,177]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" pagination="359 - 438" refId="ref76809" refString="Shinohara, A. (2002 b) Systematics of the leaf-rolling or webspinning sawfly subfamily Pamphiliinae: a preliminary overview. In: Viitasaari, M. (Ed.), Sawflies (Hymenoptera, Symphyta) I. Tremex Press, Helsinki, pp. 359 - 438." type="book chapter" year="2002">Shinohara 2002b</bibRefCitation>
for more details). Morphologically, this is regarded as a monophyletic group having the following autapomorphies: anterior part of malar space with setiferous area (female) or pit (male) (
<figureCitation box="[871,941,223,249]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="38.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[164,1422,181,1915]" captionTargetId="figure-26@38.[164,1422,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURE 2. Key to tribes and genera 2" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876497" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876497/files/figure.png" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
: 3a); supraocular area in male with narrow, dull, densely pubescent patch; facial crests in male developed, sharply carinate (e.g., 
<figureCitation box="[1123,1223,259,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 34" captionStartId="123.[151,250,1869,1893]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1844]" captionTargetId="figure-19@123.[151,1435,181,1845]" captionTargetPageId="123" captionText="FIGURE 34. Onycholyda armata, male, Korea – (a) dorsally, (b) lateroventrally, (c) head &amp; thorax dorsally, (d) head &amp; thorax ventrolaterally, (e) face, (f) antenna, (g) malar space setae, (h) claw." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876574" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876574/files/figure.png" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Figs 34e</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1236,1279,259,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 39" captionStartId="128.[151,250,1869,1893]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1843]" captionTargetId="figure-26@128.[151,1435,181,1845]" captionTargetPageId="128" captionText="FIGURE 39. Onycholyda nigroclypeata, male, Korea – (a) dorsally, (b) lateroventrally, (c) head &amp; thorax dorsally, (d) head &amp; thorax ventrolaterally, (e) face, (f) genitalia dorsally, (g) genitalia ventrally, (h) antenna." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876588" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876588/files/figure.png" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">39e</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1292,1336,259,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 43" captionStartId="132.[151,250,1869,1893]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1843]" captionTargetId="figure-26@132.[151,1435,181,1845]" captionTargetPageId="132" captionText="FIGURE 43. Onycholyda sertata, male, Russia – (a) dorsally, (b) lateroventrally, (c) head &amp; thorax dorsally, (d) head &amp; thorax ventrolaterally, (e) face, (f) genitalia dorsally, (g) genitalia ventrally, (h) antenna, (i) claw." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876606" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876606/files/figure.png" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">43e</figureCitation>
); ventral inner surface of fore tibia with disconnected row of scale-like setae; tarsal claws with acute basal lobe (
<figureCitation box="[1312,1381,295,321]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="38.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[164,1422,181,1915]" captionTargetId="figure-26@38.[164,1422,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURE 2. Key to tribes and genera 2" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876497" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876497/files/figure.png" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
: 3c). The monophyly of this genus is also supported by our molecular analyses, as discussed above.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="62" pageNumber="63" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="62.[151,1437,151,1293]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">
<bibRefCitation author="Shinohara, A." box="[199,409,367,393]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" pagination="359 - 438" refId="ref76809" refString="Shinohara, A. (2002 b) Systematics of the leaf-rolling or webspinning sawfly subfamily Pamphiliinae: a preliminary overview. In: Viitasaari, M. (Ed.), Sawflies (Hymenoptera, Symphyta) I. Tremex Press, Helsinki, pp. 359 - 438." type="book chapter" year="2002">Shinohara (2002b)</bibRefCitation>
divided the world species of this genus into two species groups, the 
<taxonomicName box="[1179,1316,367,393]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amplecta">
<emphasis box="[1179,1316,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">O. amplecta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group and the 
<taxonomicName box="[194,350,403,429]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="luteicornis">
<emphasis box="[194,350,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">O. luteicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group, based on morphology. In our molecular work, 14 species of the 
<taxonomicName box="[1174,1313,403,429]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amplecta">
<emphasis box="[1174,1313,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">O. amplecta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group and five species of the 
<taxonomicName box="[367,523,439,465]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="luteicornis">
<emphasis box="[367,523,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">O. luteicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group were used for the COI analysis, and 10 species of the 
<taxonomicName box="[1224,1363,439,465]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amplecta">
<emphasis box="[1224,1363,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">O. amplecta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group and four species of the 
<taxonomicName box="[415,570,475,501]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="luteicornis">
<emphasis box="[415,570,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">O. luteicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group were used for the NaK analysis. In general, interspecific relationships were poorly resolved in our 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Benes" authorityYear="1972" box="[467,602,511,537]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[467,602,511,537]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Onycholyda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
trees. In the COI analysis (
<figureCitation box="[908,1008,511,537]" captionStart="FIGURE 138" captionStartId="227.[151,250,1515,1539]" captionTargetBox="[157,1427,187,1487]" captionTargetId="figure-19@227.[151,1436,181,1491]" captionTargetPageId="227" captionText="FIGURE 138. Condensed ML tree based on CO1 gene sequences, with details of Onycholyda, part 1." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876837" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876837/files/figure.png" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Figs 138</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1020,1065,511,537]" captionStart="FIGURE 139" captionStartId="228.[151,250,1667,1691]" captionTargetBox="[157,1426,190,1638]" captionTargetId="figure-26@228.[151,1436,181,1643]" captionTargetPageId="228" captionText="FIGURE 139. Condensed ML tree based on CO1 gene sequences, with details of Onycholyda, part 2." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876841" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876841/files/figure.png" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">139</figureCitation>
), three Nearctic species of the 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="luteicornis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">O. luteicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group (
<taxonomicName box="[361,517,547,573]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="luteicornis">
<emphasis box="[361,517,547,573]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">O. luteicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[531,699,547,573]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigritibialis">
<emphasis box="[531,699,547,573]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">O. nigritibialis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[755,885,547,573]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sitkensis">
<emphasis box="[755,885,547,573]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">O. sitkensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) formed a clade, though with only 61% UFBoot support, but two Palaearctic species of this species group (
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Maa" baseAuthorityYear="1949" box="[823,940,583,609]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="armata">
<emphasis box="[823,940,583,609]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">O. armata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[999,1184,583,609]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kumamotonis">
<emphasis box="[999,1184,583,609]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">O. kumamotonis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) were rather distantly separated from them and located among the members of the 
<taxonomicName box="[827,964,619,645]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amplecta">
<emphasis box="[827,964,619,645]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">O. amplecta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group. In the NaK analysis (
<figureCitation box="[1285,1382,618,645]" captionStart="FIGURE 153" captionStartId="240.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[178,1407,186,1910]" captionTargetId="figure-26@240.[172,1415,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="240" captionText="FIGURE 153. Condensed ML tree based on NaK gene sequences, with details of Onycholyda." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876872" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876872/files/figure.png" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Fig. 153</figureCitation>
), the two Palaearctic species of the 
<taxonomicName box="[484,637,655,681]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="luteicornis">
<emphasis box="[484,637,655,681]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">O. luteicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group (
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Maa" baseAuthorityYear="1949" box="[723,837,655,681]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="armata">
<emphasis box="[723,837,655,681]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">O. armata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[890,1072,655,681]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kumamotonis">
<emphasis box="[890,1072,655,681]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">O. kumamotonis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) were retrieved as monophyletic with 100% UFBoot support and the two Nearctic species of this species group (
<taxonomicName box="[1050,1205,691,717]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="luteicornis">
<emphasis box="[1050,1205,691,717]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">O. luteicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1260,1427,691,717]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigritibialis">
<emphasis box="[1260,1427,691,717]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">O. nigritibialis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) were also retrieved as monophyletic with 95% UFBoot support, but these Palaearctic and Nearctic clades did not form a clade and were recovered among the members of the 
<taxonomicName box="[816,952,763,789]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amplecta">
<emphasis box="[816,952,763,789]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">O. amplecta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group. Thus, the result of our COI and NaK analyses did not support the dichotomous division of the genus into species groups advocated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Shinohara, A." box="[1221,1433,799,825]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" pagination="359 - 438" refId="ref76809" refString="Shinohara, A. (2002 b) Systematics of the leaf-rolling or webspinning sawfly subfamily Pamphiliinae: a preliminary overview. In: Viitasaari, M. (Ed.), Sawflies (Hymenoptera, Symphyta) I. Tremex Press, Helsinki, pp. 359 - 438." type="book chapter" year="2002">Shinohara (2002b)</bibRefCitation>
. On the other hand, it is interesting that in the COI tree all the 17 Nearctic specimens of six species were retrieved as a monophyletic group with 99% UFBoot support and each of the 
<taxonomicName box="[888,1026,871,897]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amplecta">
<emphasis box="[888,1026,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">O. amplecta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group (
<taxonomicName box="[1115,1252,871,897]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amplecta">
<emphasis box="[1115,1252,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">O. amplecta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[1266,1436,871,897]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufofasciata">
<emphasis box="[1266,1436,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">O. rufofasciata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[199,375,907,933]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="multisignata">
<emphasis box="[199,375,907,933]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">O. multisignata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and the 
<taxonomicName box="[482,637,907,933]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="luteicornis">
<emphasis box="[482,637,907,933]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">O. luteicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group (
<taxonomicName box="[728,883,907,933]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="luteicornis">
<emphasis box="[728,883,907,933]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">O. luteicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[897,1064,907,933]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigritibialis">
<emphasis box="[897,1064,907,933]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">O. nigritibialis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1121,1251,907,933]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sitkensis">
<emphasis box="[1121,1251,907,933]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">O. sitkensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) formed a clade with low UFBoot support of 61%. The intrageneric relationships in 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Benes" authorityYear="1972" box="[910,1045,943,969]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[910,1045,943,969]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Onycholyda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
still need a revision.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="62.[151,1437,151,1293]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">
This genus is most diverse in warm temperate regions of eastern Asia. There are 42 valid species worldwide (
<bibRefCitation author="Taeger, A. &amp; Blank, S. M. &amp; Liston, A. D." box="[158,371,1015,1041]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" pagination="1 - 1064" refId="ref80219" refString="Taeger, A., Blank, S. M. &amp; Liston, A. D. (2010) World catalog of Symphyta (Hymenoptera). Zootaxa, 2580 (1), 1 - 1064. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 2580.1.1" type="journal article" year="2010">
Taeger 
<emphasis box="[245,303,1015,1041]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">et al.</emphasis>
2010
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Shinohara, A. &amp; Wei, M. - C." box="[383,647,1015,1041]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" pagination="53 - 74" refId="ref79164" refString="Shinohara, A. &amp; Wei, M. - C. (2012) Pamphiliid sawflies (Hymenoptera, Symphyta) of Mt. Yunshan, Hunan Province, China. Memoirs of the National Museum of Nature and Science, Tokyo, 48, 53 - 74." type="journal article" year="2012">Shinohara &amp; Wei 2012</bibRefCitation>
, 2016; 
<bibRefCitation author="Shinohara, A. &amp; Kiyoshi, T. &amp; Wei, M. - C. &amp; Kameda, Y." box="[732,992,1015,1041]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" pagination="75 - 81" refId="ref78172" refString="Shinohara, A., Kiyoshi, T., Wei, M. - C. &amp; Kameda, Y. (2018 c) Identification of larvae and recognition of new synonymy for two Chinese Onycholyda sawflies (Insecta: Hymenoptera: Pamphiliidae) based on molecular data. Species Diversity, 23, 75 - 81. https: // doi. org / 10.12782 / specdiv. 23.75" type="journal article" year="2018">
Shinohara 
<emphasis box="[854,912,1015,1041]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">et al.</emphasis>
2018c
</bibRefCitation>
), of which 32 occur in eastern Asia. In the Russian Far East and 
<collectingCountry box="[434,505,1051,1077]" name="South Korea" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Korea</collectingCountry>
, only eight 
<taxonomicName box="[635,858,1051,1077]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">
<emphasis box="[635,770,1051,1077]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Onycholyda</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
have been found, whereas ten species are known to occur in 
<collectingCountry box="[249,313,1087,1113]" name="Japan" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Japan</collectingCountry>
and 19 species in 
<collectingCountry box="[519,590,1087,1113]" name="China" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">China</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="62.[151,1437,151,1293]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">
The larvae of 
<taxonomicName box="[359,584,1123,1149]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">
<emphasis box="[359,494,1123,1149]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Onycholyda</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
feed on the host leaves singly or gregariously in simple leaf-rolls or, when they become larger, often in webs. All known larvae feed on shrubby or herbaceous 
<taxonomicName box="[1080,1189,1159,1185]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Rosaceae</taxonomicName>
, except for one doubtful record of 
<taxonomicName box="[296,378,1195,1221]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cornaceae" genus="Cornus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Cornales" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[296,378,1195,1221]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Cornus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[392,514,1195,1221]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cornaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Cornales" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Cornaceae</taxonomicName>
) in North America (
<bibRefCitation author="Middlekauff, W. W." box="[735,942,1195,1221]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" pagination="1 - 84" refId="ref75014" refString="Middlekauff, W. W. (1964) The North American sawflies of the genus Pamphilius (Hymenoptera: Pamphiliidae). University of California, Publications in Entomology, 38, 1 - 84." type="journal article" year="1964">Middlekauff 1964</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Shinohara, A. &amp; Ibuki, S. &amp; Kakuda, T. &amp; Kameda, Y." box="[953,1195,1195,1221]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" pagination="343 - 350" refId="ref77902" refString="Shinohara, A., Ibuki, S., Kakuda, T. &amp; Kameda, Y. (2019) Pamphilius japonicus feeds on Cornus: the first Old World record of Pamphiliidae (Hymenoptera) associated with Cornaceae. Zootaxa, 4585 (2), 343 - 350. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4585.2.7" type="journal article" year="2019">
Shinohara 
<emphasis box="[1073,1128,1195,1221]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">et al.</emphasis>
2019
</bibRefCitation>
). Most species are associated with the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[418,488,1231,1257]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Rubus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[418,488,1231,1257]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Rubus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and a few with the genera 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Kangas &amp; Syrjanen" baseAuthorityYear="1962" box="[787,918,1231,1257]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Filipendula" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[787,918,1231,1257]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Filipendula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[971,1091,1231,1257]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Agrimonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[971,1091,1231,1257]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Agrimonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Middlekauff, W. W." box="[1104,1311,1231,1257]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" pagination="1 - 84" refId="ref75014" refString="Middlekauff, W. W. (1964) The North American sawflies of the genus Pamphilius (Hymenoptera: Pamphiliidae). University of California, Publications in Entomology, 38, 1 - 84." type="journal article" year="1964">Middlekauff 1964</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Shinohara, A." pageId="62" pageNumber="63" pagination="359 - 438" refId="ref76809" refString="Shinohara, A. (2002 b) Systematics of the leaf-rolling or webspinning sawfly subfamily Pamphiliinae: a preliminary overview. In: Viitasaari, M. (Ed.), Sawflies (Hymenoptera, Symphyta) I. Tremex Press, Helsinki, pp. 359 - 438." type="book chapter" year="2002">Shinohara 2002b</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Shinohara, A. &amp; Wei, M. - C." box="[236,495,1267,1293]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" pagination="105 - 107" refId="ref79117" refString="Shinohara, A. &amp; Wei, M. - C. (2010) Discovery of host plant and larva of Onycholyda odaesana (Hymenoptera, Pamphiliidae) in Hunan Province, China. Japanese Journal of Systematic Entomology, 16, 105 - 107." type="journal article" year="2010">Shinohara &amp; Wei 2010</bibRefCitation>
, 2016; 
<bibRefCitation author="Shinohara, A. &amp; Lee, H. - S." box="[577,833,1267,1293]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" pagination="209 - 212" refId="ref78457" refString="Shinohara, A. &amp; Lee, H. - S. (2011) Host plants and larvae of two leaf-rolling sawfly species of the genus Onycholyda (Hymenoptera, Pamphiliidae) in Korea. Japanese Journal of Systematic Entomology, 17, 209 - 212." type="journal article" year="2011">Shinohara &amp; Lee 2011</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Shinohara, A. &amp; Kakuda, T. &amp; Wei, M. - C. &amp; Kameda, Y." box="[845,1101,1267,1293]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" pagination="123 - 132" refId="ref77967" refString="Shinohara, A., Kakuda, T., Wei, M. - C. &amp; Kameda, Y. (2018 b) DNA barcodes identify the larvae and unassociated male of three Onycholyda sawflies (Hymenoptera, Pamphiliidae) from China. Zootaxa, 4403 (1), 123 - 132. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4403.1.7" type="journal article" year="2018">
Shinohara 
<emphasis box="[965,1022,1267,1293]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">et al.</emphasis>
2018b
</bibRefCitation>
, c).
</paragraph>
